  "articleSummary": "The article argues that Google's self-driving cars are involved in more accidents than human drivers, but these crashes are caused by human drivers unfamiliar with robotic behavior, not by the AI itself. It analyzes the ethical and legal dilemmas (the trolley problem) arising from the cars' absolute adherence to traffic laws, which makes them overly cautious and vulnerable to rear-end collisions. The author proposes a three-tier perception system that balances strict rule-following with flexible, context-aware adjustments to improve safety and integration. The tone is analytical with a persuasive edge, targeting a general tech-interested audience interested in the practical and ethical challenges of autonomous vehicles.",
